@node press7 "Omega RIPort - Edited by David Tiberio"
@toc main

 - PRESIDENT OF MAJOR COMPUTER FIRM IN ASSASSINATION ATTEMPT -
       AP Newswire  --  Westchester, PA  --  May 4th 1994

   An incident that has rocked the financial markets and sent Wall Street
executives into mourning is finally being disclosed by the Westchester
Police Department.  In a brief statement, SLieutenant John Dillulo detailed
an attack on the brilliant business genius Mehdi Ali.  According to
Lt Dillulo:
   "At approxiamately 2:30 pm, on the private airstrip of Mr. Ali, an
assassin gunned down Mehdi Ali as he sipped a margarita while waiting for
his limousine to arrive.  It is unclear at this time what the motive of
the assailant was, but we have reason to believe that he is a member of
a terrorist cell operating in the United States."
   Lt Dillulo was asked by reporters about this terrorist theory, and
he had this to say.  "The assailant was in an extremely distressed state
of mind, and was heard by several witnesses to shout 'Omega!' as he
fired.  We have proof that this is the name of a terrorist network that
is operating in Europe, and has a small following in the States."
   According to FBI records, a similar cell in Australia was finally
defeated after as-yet-undefined cooperation given by Mehdi Ali, as well
as his partner, Irving Gould.  Mr. Gould said, "This is a tragic day
for businessman everywhere.  It's hard to believe that so brilliant a
man could be taken from us.  I vow to break the back of this 'Omega'
group."
   As news first broke about the assassination, General Alexander Haig,
a member of the board of directors that had profitted well under Mr.
Ali's brilliant leadership of CBM, called an emergency press conference.
Gen. Haig assuaged fears that there would be a power vacuum created by
the death of Mr. Ali and the difficulty in finding Irving Gould, who
was later found to be vacationing in the Bahamas.  Haig unequivocally
asserted "that everything is under control, and that I'm taking charge."
Many reporters later admitted to an odd feeling of deja-vue at these
remarks, but were unable to explain further.
   There will be a national day of mourning and Mehdi Ali will lie in
state so that the millions of admirers may pay their last respects to
him.  A day of silence will be observed by all advertisers as a tribute
to Mr. Ali's innovative use of advertising-in-absentia.

Jay Goodwin - Omega RIPort staff reporter
fallous@ksuvm.ksu.edu

@endnode
