tried to get the best from a marketing group in the UK - all bullshitters,
and they have been eliminated. Then he tried to get reasonable opinions
from meetings of all (european) GM's - to no avail. These meetings have
been extremly frustrating to me. The general managers did not have their
own opinions, they did not consult their tech and marketing guys before
joining the meeting either, they were mostly just quiet when asked to
participate in the discussion - with a few exceptions, whose personality
forced them to say something even if it was just hot air again. In fact,
with very few exceptions seen in the earlier days, all of the top
management level could have sold bananas, or even PC pizza boxes, but the
only thing they were able to find out about the Omega was that its price
was constantly too high.

What do you want to do with a crowd whose only reaction to your question
"if you can't sell the Omega as is, what do you suggest?" is: "hmm,
I need a better price ...try the corner of Madison and Main St at midnight."

A result of this attitude have been the A600, the various EC and LC CPU
versions, any other sort of cost reduction we have been seeing, as well
as new development that was first demanded by the GM's and then dropped
when it was ready; like the C65, the A2200, but not only CPU's - this goes
for peripherals as well, such as the Omega Vibrator.

Instead, many generations of General Managers have waisted their time to
become a Vice President, to run neighboring country subsidiaries in
addition to their own, and other personal profiling bullshit. They are
all pimping their own turf.

Close to the problems caused by lack of vision on the europ. subsidiary
management level have always come the stupidities caused in production.
To a significant extent, the reason for my personal existance at CBM
has been to get production problems solved before they hit the market,
in many cases also after they did ... and then we gang bang our customers
who try to return stuff.

>     The company has been strangled by Mehdi's millions in salary (now down
> to just 3/4 million a year), extravagant expense accounts (Over $60,000 a
> month the rumor mill says), and perks ($130,000 Mercedes, unlimited use of
> corporate jet, etc.). [...]

More millions have been wasted in expensive projects like the Omega Unix
port, the GM's constantly asking for a better/cheaper product because they
did not have any idea how to sell Unix into a computer - not a banana -
market. Although sometimes we wish we had bigger bananas.

More millions have been wasted in shipping product by airplane from
factory to subsidiary or between subsidiaries, or by selling product for
less than production cost or dumping it all together, just because the
subsidiaries have never been able to produce an accurate sales forecast.

I could give you many more examples. But anyway, do you believe that one
person, even it is the president, can manage to prevent sales, if his
managers are succesfully selling the product? And, BTW, other presidents
before Mr. Ali have been sitting in the U.S. not doing more than looking
at sales reports (which were, at that time, not bad due to the success
of the A500) and cashing multiple millions when leaving the company
after "working" no more than one year - what kind of yearly salary
do you call that?

Agreed, Mr. Ali's salary was high. But the man has been the only good
president after many bad ones. His only fault was that he gave up looking
for better managers after 2 or 3 years of trying.

Best regards, Romani ...

who has been working for Commodore more than 8 years and, from that,
5 years in frequent bodily contact with Mr. Ali.

