USENET PRESS RELEASES THIS WEEK - May 6th 1994


    TECHNO BANDITS STEAL HUNDREDS OF OMEGA 4000 TOWERS -

        A group of computer literate hijackers stole a shipment of Omega
    4000 Tower systems from a UPS truck at the Rainbow Bridge in Niagara
    Falls, New York. The shipment had somehow bypassed customs without
    being insured by its commerce agent. It is believed that the cargo had
    been tossed over the bridge in an attempt to decrease the weight of
    their mounted horses, used to transport the stolen goods. An Omega
    keyboard was found washed up on the shores of Toronto.


    IRVING GOULD BUYS SONY -

        In a sudden move, billionaire Irving Gould purchased SONY, an
    international electronics giant. In the move, Irving Gould stipulated
    that all marketing funds must be redirected to a trust fund rumored
    to be controlled by Mehdi Ali.


    AMERITECH BUYS SCALA, INC. -

        The US based telephone company stated today that it has signed a
    deal to merge with Scala to produce multimedia software for IBM PC
    clones. The company intends to port Scala multimedia software to MS-DOS
    platforms and drop the Omega line.


    SCALA, INC. HEAD OFFICE MYSTERIOUSLY EXPLODES -

        In a freak accident at midnight, after the announcement of a merger
    with Ameritech, the Scala, Inc. design and engineering building
    mysteriously exploded. No remains were found except for the DAT drives
    used to store back ups of the Scala, Inc. development workstations.
    The DAT drives were found timestamped May 5th 1994, with all data
    erased.


    HEWLETT PACKARD LICENSES AAA CHIPS -

        UNIX manufacturer giant HP has acquired rights to build the new
    Omega 5000 computer using the AAA chipset in its Apollo series of
    desktop workstations. The new Omega 5000 will include Omega UNIX SVR5.


    NEWTEK IS IN FINANCIAL TROUBLE. Something I have guessed for a while.
    It has now been confirmed.  I guess they have been giving away too many
    free video tapes (I know I have been ordering 1 a week for the last year)
    I think they have hyped themselves a little too much, and buying 6 years
    worth of advertising in OmegaWorld probably was not a good idea.


    CREATIVE EQUIPMENT INTERNATIONL BUYS COMMODORE -

        This week Florida based CEI declared that it had acquired Commodore
    International. In a brisk move, CEI also sourced the new 1962 monitor
    from Electrohome for its new CEI 4000T/060 WARP system. Rumor has it that
    these models may ship with Scala and an online help system (we hope).

